Second try for tax cut in Oakland=20
Smaller utility levy likely after Brown veto=20
Tyche Hendricks, Chronicle Staff Writer
Tuesday, May 1, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/01/M
NE216500.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Oakland -- The Oakland City Council is set to scale back plans for a=20
six-month cut in the city's utility users tax in the face of a first-ever=
=20
veto by Mayor Jerry Brown, who said the city may not be able to afford the=
=20
cut.=20
A week after the council voted 5 to 2 to give residents relief on their=20
skyrocketing gas and electric bills by reducing the tax the city imposes,=
=20
council members said yesterday that they will reconsider the plan and may=
=20
give a break only to the poorest Oaklanders.=20
City Council President Ignacio De La Fuente, the author of the tax cut=20
proposal, said he plans to revise the measure at tonight's council meeting.=
=20
Under the revision, low-income residents would be exempt from the tax, whic=
h=20
could cost the city an estimated $300,000.=20
"The mayor has some legitimate concerns," De La Fuente said. He said he wou=
ld=20
postpone consideration of a cut for all residents until after the state has=
=20
approved its budget for the coming year.=20
The council's latest move came after Brown last week invoked his authority =
to=20
block legislation, a power he was granted under the 1998 strong-mayor=20
ordinance that he wrote and voters approved.=20
In the letter, Brown said the six-month tax break would take $1.6 million=
=20
from the city coffers and could be construed as a permanent tax cut, which=
=20
under state Proposition 218 would require approval by two-thirds of the=20
voters to reinstate.=20
"In addition," the mayor wrote, "the current budget hemorrhaging in=20
Sacramento threatens to reduce expected state revenues to the city on which=
=20
the current city budget is based." Brown said he would support relief for=
=20
those least able to pay.=20
The council had planned to temporarily reduce the city's utility tax from 7=
.=20
5 percent to roughly 6 percent for most residents and eliminate it entirely=
=20
for low-income households that qualify for PG&E's assistance program.=20
After the council approved the tax cut last week, city leaders heard a repo=
rt=20
from the city manager's budget analyst confirming that state money for=20
California's cities might be reduced for the next fiscal year.=20
"We all wanted to do this," said Councilwoman Jane Brunner, referring to=20
herself and four other council members, including De La Fuente, who voted f=
or=20
the utility tax relief.=20
"But they are saying that the (state's) energy costs may dip into some of t=
he=20
regular general fund money (for city and county governments). And that may =
be=20
very significant."=20
Councilwoman Nancy Nadel, who voted against the tax cut along with Dick=20
Spees, said tax relief for low-income residents would cost the city roughly=
=20
$300,000, which she called a more reasonable figure. The eighth council=20
position was vacant last week but will be filled tonight when council membe=
r-=20
elect Moses Mayne is sworn in.=20
Brown's action marks the first time he has exercised his law-blocking power=
=20
under Measure X, which allows the mayor to send new legislation back to the=
=20
council for reconsideration if it is passed with fewer than six votes.=20
If the council cannot muster six votes on its second review, the law would=
=20
not take effect.=20
Russo said the fact that Brown has not used his veto power until now, more=
=20
than halfway into his four-year term, shows that he is able to work with th=
e=20
council.=20
"I think it's significant that this is first time (he's used the veto)," sa=
id=20
Russo. "It has been 2 1/2 years of some pretty controversial and contentiou=
s=20
stuff."=20
