Warning of a summer power 'Armageddon'=20
Davis aide paints dire scenario in push for bonds to buy power=20
Lynda Gledhill, Greg Lucas, Chronicle Sacramento Bureau
Tuesday, May 1, 2001=20
,2001 San Francisco Chronicle=20
URL:=20
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/chronicle/archive/2001/05=
/01/M
N192706.DTL&type=3Dnews=20
Sacramento -- Trying to drum up support to issue $12.5 billion in bonds to=
=20
buy power, a top adviser to Gov. Gray Davis warned lawmakers yesterday of=
=20
"Armageddon" this summer if key assumptions on energy generation and=20
conservation fail to materialize.=20
Presenting a 67-page document to lawmakers, Davis' top energy consultants=
=20
said numerous assumptions -- such as increased conservation and more=20
alternative generating facilities returning to full operation -- must pan=
=20
out.=20
Without that, Davis' Cabinet secretary, Susan Kennedy, said an "Armageddon=
=20
scenario" would take place, according to numerous lawmakers in the meeting.=
=20
That could include more blackouts or additional borrowing, Kennedy said in =
a=20
briefing later with reporters. "Everything has to fall in place."=20
But one key assumption was immediately blasted by an energy industry offici=
al=20
as "completely unrealistic."=20
The administration document forecasts that 90 percent of the state's=20
alternative generators will be back on line by June. About one-third are=20
currently not operating because they are not being paid by California's deb=
t-=20
ridden utilities.=20
"That is complete lunacy at this point," said Jerry Bloom, a spokesman for=
=20
the California Cogeneration Council. "The assumption simply does not reflec=
t=20
the reality of the market. It shows once again that the governor is not=20
listening."=20
Among the other assumptions is a 7 percent conservation rate and the approv=
al=20
of the deal between the state and Southern California Edison Co. for the=20
purchase of the utility's transmission lines. Davis has set a target of=20
conserving 10 percent.=20
In San Francisco yesterday, Davis told a high-tech business conference that=
=20
the state will have to walk a tightrope to get through the summer.=20
"We are going to have to set the Guinness Book of Records in this state in=
=20
order to avoid disruptions this summer," he said.=20
State Treasurer Phil Angelides said the assumptions were "fair and rational=
"=20
but warned many of the assumptions are beyond the state's control.=20
"The biggest threat to making this plan work is if generators take prices=
=20
from the current level, which is horrendous, to obscenely horrendous," he=
=20
said after meeting with Assembly Republicans for an hour on the proposed bo=
nd=20
sale.=20
The dire scenarios were used by the administration officials to convince=20
Assembly Republicans to approve a bond authorization, which is scheduled to=
=20
come up for a vote on Thursday.=20
GOP members balked at approving the huge bond issuance without further=20
details from the administration. But yesterday's information simply raised=
=20
more questions in many minds.=20
"It's kind of like peeling back an onion -- as you peel something back you=
=20
find something else out," said Assemblyman George Runner, R-Lancaster.=20
Assemblyman Tony Strickland, R-Thousand Oaks, said Republicans want to be=
=20
sure there won't be a continuing need to issue larger amounts of bonds in t=
he=20
future.=20
"The governor's office is asking us to approve the biggest bond in American=
=20
history, and we're just supposed to trust them on a lot of this stuff," he=
=20
said. "What happens if the assumptions don't happen? Do we need another $7=
=20
billion or $10 billion in loans? Is the existing rate structure enough or=
=20
will they ask for more? We want to know."=20
Republican votes are needed to approve the bond issuing authority on an=20
urgency basis.=20
The current bill only allows for $10 billion, but the administration now sa=
ys=20
it needs $12.5 billion. Kennedy said another request for more financing wil=
l=20
be made later to close that gap.=20
The predictions use the rate increase proposed by Davis, which averages abo=
ut=20
37 percent. His rate increase would pay off not only the revenue bond issue=
d=20
by the state, but also a $8 billion bond issued by the utilities to pay off=
=20
some of their back debt.=20
Angelides has pressed for the bonding authority because the commitments for=
=20
short-term bridge loans -- which would provide the state with money during=
=20
the several weeks it would take to issue the bonds -- expire on May 8.=20
However, most of the GOP members of the Assembly said they have not been=20
convinced of the need for the bridge loans.=20
Runner said normal budgetary borrowing will keep the general fund whole unt=
il=20
the bonds can be issued. Republicans believe the emphasis on the short term=
=20
funding is to allow Davis to present a rosier budget later this month.=20
Tim Gage, Davis' director of finance, said the authorization is needed=20
immediately to give sellers confidence that the state is credit-worthy and=
=20
can continue to purchase power. Currently, the state is being charged a=20
credit premium, he said.=20
"I'm deeply concerned if the bridge loan, the first step, doesn't come=20
together it will do harm getting the energy bond to the market," Angelides=
=20
said.=20
Meanwhile, the state Public Utilities Commission yesterday accused Pacific=
=20
Gas & Electric Co. of trying to use bankruptcy to escape state regulation a=
nd=20
raise rates drastically.=20
The PUC asked a federal bankruptcy judge to dismiss PG&E's challenge to=20
accounting changes ordered by the state commission on March 27 that would=
=20
make it harder for the utility to pass along to customers its $8.9 billion=
=20
debt for electricity purchases.=20
Chronicle staff writers Bob Egelko and Tanya Schevitz contributed to this=
=20
story.=20
E-mail Lynda Gledhill at lgledhill@sfchronicle.com and Greg Lucas at=20
glucas@sfchronicle.com.=20
