Cheney rejects conservation=20
Posted at 11:03 p.m. PDT Monday, April 30, 2001=20
BY JIM PUZZANGHERA=20

Mercury News Washington Bureau=20


WASHINGTON -- The energy woes of California and the nation cannot be solved=
=20
with price controls or conservation, but only by increasing the country's=
=20
supply of oil and natural gas and using more coal and nuclear power, Vice=
=20
President Dick Cheney said Monday.=20
Cheney was laying the groundwork for the announcement later this month of a=
=20
major energy proposal. The vice president argued that without adopting the=
=20
Bush administration plan, California's energy crisis may spread to the rest=
=20
of the country.=20
``A few years ago, many people had never heard the term `rolling blackout.'=
=20
Now, everybody in California knows the term all too well. And the rest of=
=20
America is starting to wonder when these rolling blackouts might roll over=
=20
them,'' Cheney said in a Toronto speech to the Associated Press.=20
``Without a clear, coherent energy strategy for the nation, all Americans=
=20
could one day go through what Californians are experiencing now, or worse,'=
'=20
warned Cheney, who leads the administration's high-level energy task force.=
=20
Cheney's speech was notable more for its tone than its substance. Much of t=
he=20
detail he offered is similar to what Energy Secretary Spencer Abraham laid=
=20
out last month. He reiterated the need for more than 1,300 new power plants=
=20
and 38,000 miles of additional natural gas pipeline. Cheney also repeated a=
n=20
administration claim that the area to be opened for drilling in Alaska's=20
environmentally sensitive Arctic National Wildlife Refuge would be smaller=
=20
than Washington's Dulles airport.=20
But Cheney, who ran a Texas company that provided services to the energy=20
industry, used blunt language to dismiss the idea that conservation could b=
e=20
a major solution to the problem.=20
``The aim here is efficiency, not austerity,'' Cheney said, rejecting the=
=20
notion that Americans should be told to ``do more with less.''=20
``Conservation may be a sign of personal virtue, but it is not a sufficient=
=20
basis for a sound, comprehensive energy policy,'' he said.=20
Contrast with Gov. Davis=20
Large-scale conservation is one of California Gov. Gray Davis' efforts for=
=20
getting through this summer without extensive blackouts. Earlier this=20
monthLast month, Davis approved an $850 million energy conservation plan th=
at=20
offers incentives to try to shave at least 2,000 megawatts during peak hour=
s=20
from the state's electricity usage.=20
Davis on Monday blasted condemned Bush and Cheney for belittling conservati=
on=20
programs.=20
``It's clear that the Bush administration has an energy bias. Both the=20
president and the vice president come from an oil- and gas-producing state.=
=20
That is their bias,'' Davis said, referring to Bush's Texas oil roots and=
=20
Cheney's tenure as the head of Texas-based Halliburton Co. ``And I do belie=
ve=20
we should build more plants and produce more energy, but at the same time, =
we=20
must become more energy-efficient.''=20
Davis and other California officials have also pushed the administration to=
=20
limit the price of electricity throughout the West this summer. Although=20
federal regulators approved measures last week designed to rein in the cost=
=20
of electricity in California, the plan fell far short of hard price caps.=
=20
Cheney on Monday restated the White House's opposition to price caps, sayin=
g=20
they were among a number of the ``usual quick fixes'' that have failed to=
=20
solve the problem over the years.=20
``Price controls, tapping strategic reserves, creating new federal agencies=
=20
-- if these were any solution, we'd have resolved the problems a long time=
=20
ago,'' Cheney said.=20
Other sources rejected=20
The vice president rejected the idea that alternative sources of energy cou=
ld=20
replace our dependence on fossil fuels such as oil, gas and coal, at least=
=20
for a long time.=20
``The reality is that fossil fuels supply virtually a hundred percent of ou=
r=20
transportation needs and an overwhelming share of our electricity=20
requirements,'' he said. ``For years down the road, this will continue to b=
e=20
true.''=20
The solution, he said, is to find more oil and natural gas by to increase=
=20
drilling for oil and natural gas in the United States, making more use of=
=20
find new ways to burn coal more cleanly and put a renewed emphasis on nucle=
ar=20
power.=20
``Fortunately for the environment, one-fifth of our electricity is nuclear=
=20
generated,'' he said. ``If we're serious about environmental protection, th=
en=20
we must seriously question the wisdom of backing away from what is, as a=20
matter of record, a safe, clean and very plentiful energy source.''=20
Carl Pope, executive director of the Sierra Club, said the White House is=
=20
trying to convince people that their plan to ramp up increase energy=20
production, even at the expense of environmental concerns, is the only way =
to=20
solve the energy problems.=20
``From the beginning, the administration has wanted to tell the American=20
people that they didn't have any choice, that the only way they could=20
transport themselves to work, heat their houses, toast their toast .?.?. wa=
s=20
to ruin the environment,'' he said.=20
The environmental leader saw a sign of desperation, however, in Cheney's=20
speech. ``They've been out pushing this agenda for a hundred days and the=
=20
American people are rejecting it,'' Pope said.=20
Bush's low grade=20
Several recent polls have shown Bush scoring low on his handling of=20
environmental and energy issues. A Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll releas=
ed=20
last week, showed 61 percent of respondents rated Bush's performance on=20
energy as ``only fair'' or ``poor.''=20
Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Palo Alto, said the administration was going backward wi=
th=20
its proposals. She joined with more than 30 of her colleagues from Californ=
ia=20
and Washington to write to Secretary Abraham on Monday to criticize the=20
handling of the energy crisis.=20
``We can do much better than this,'' Eshoo said of the crystallizing White=
=20
House plan. ``I don't think we need to sacrifice our environment in order t=
o=20
move ahead.''=20

Mercury News Staff Writer Michael Bazeley contributed to this report.=20
