Federal energy regulators propose surcharge plan to pay utilities' debt=20
Posted at 5:51 a.m. PDT Tuesday, May 1, 2001=20
SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A surcharge on wholesale electricity prices has been=
=20
proposed by federal energy regulators as a way to pay utilities' debts.=20
The move angers state officials who say the suggestion amounts to gouging=
=20
customers.=20
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-California, has been an outspoken critic of the=20
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's policies in California. She said the=
=20
surcharge would ``ensure that power generators get paid fully for their pri=
ce=20
gouging.''=20
``That is outrageous and will further alienate Californians,'' she said.=20
Late last year and early this year, power companies accrued about $6 billio=
n=20
in unpaid bills from the state's ailing utilities. FERC suggested collectin=
g=20
the money to reimburse suppliers who have debts from PG&E, Southern=20
California Edison and San Diego Gas and Electric Co.=20
The surcharge would likely be levied to the state's Department of Water=20
Resources. As the state's purchasing agent, that department has spent more=
=20
than $5 billion on power since January.=20
If the proposal is approved, FERC would require the California Independent=
=20
System Operator, which runs the state's power grid, to collect the surcharg=
e.=20
``We have 30 days to comment to FERC and are considering our options,'' sai=
d=20
Sean Gallagher, state counsel at the California Public Utilities Commission=
.=20
