Record prices for power expected this summer in U.S.=20
Published Tuesday, May 1, 2001, in the San Jose Mercury News=20
BY WILLIAM CLAIBORNE=20

Washington Post=20


CHICAGO -- The rest of the United States is virtually certain to escape=20
rolling blackouts this summer like the ones that have plagued California, b=
ut=20
record price increases for electricity are likely in many places, energy=20
experts agree.=20
Despite their confidence that they can survive everything but an extremely=
=20
hot summer without power outages, managers of the nation's interconnecting=
=20
electrical power grids are anxiously awaiting new power plants that are=20
scheduled to come online. They are also promoting conservation and seeking=
=20
ways to avoid distribution logjams during peak demand periods this summer.=
=20
``We see a big distinction between California and the rest of the country,'=
'=20
said David Costello, an economist in charge of short-term forecasting for t=
he=20
Energy Information Administration, the statistical arm of the Energy=20
Department. ``We have no real reason to believe any place is unusually at=
=20
risk.''=20
But record spikes in the price of electricity are a given for this summer,=
=20
some industry analysts say, because a growing proportion of power plants ru=
n=20
on natural gas, which has doubled in price over the past year.=20
The Energy Department estimates that electricity demand will grow 2.3 perce=
nt=20
nationally this year, with much higher increases in the West and the South.=
=20
At the same time, the reserve capacity margin that utilities try to build=
=20
into their systems to handle the hottest days -- when use of air conditione=
rs=20
and other appliances taxes supplies -- has been falling in some regions to=
=20
well less than the desired 15 percent above peak summer loads.=20
That means utilities may have to import large volumes of electricity over=
=20
transmission systems that were not designed to handle them. What power=20
officials are hoping to avoid are critical shortfalls in generating capacit=
y,=20
followed by overwhelming strains on aging high-voltage transmission lines a=
s=20
power is bought and sold in increasingly competitive electricity markets.=
=20
Even though scores of new power plants have been built in the Northeast,=20
South and Midwest in recent months and many more are being planned, the=20
expected 15 percent increase in new generation will not be fully online for=
=20
another two years.=20
That leaves parts of the nation vulnerable to outages if there are prolonge=
d=20
heat waves this summer, or if utilities are unable to start up new or rebui=
lt=20
gas-fired power plants as scheduled, according to energy experts.=20
Apart from California, the worst problems are expected in adjoining western=
=20
states, as California electrical grid managers scramble to buy electricity =
at=20
a time when power production at the region's hydroelectric dams is already=
=20
being cut because of shrinking water levels in reservoirs.

