Davis calls generators on carpet=20
Published Tuesday, May 1, 2001, in the San Jose Mercury News=20
BY MICHAEL BAZELEY=20

Mercury News=20


Gov. Gray Davis has asked power generators to Sacramento next week for a=20
meeting intended to ``make sure they feel some of the pain'' of the state's=
=20
energy woes.=20
Davis and other officials have portrayed the generators -- who own the powe=
r=20
plants that supply the state's electricity -- as the black-hatted villains =
of=20
the energy crisis. Along with the utilities and consumer groups, Davis has=
=20
accused the companies of taking advantage of the energy shortage by chargin=
g=20
exorbitant prices for their power. They have denied that.=20
Davis said he would use the meeting to tell the companies ``not to rip us=
=20
off'' and to be ``good citizens.''=20
``These energy companies have made more money than any company in America,'=
'=20
Davis said at a San Francisco event to promote conservation. ``They haven't=
=20
done it by making a better product. They haven't done it by providing bette=
r=20
service. They just bought our plants and are selling us back the power at=
=20
extraordinarily unheard-of rates. .?.?. They should participate collectivel=
y=20
in the solution of this problem.''=20
Davis said he also would meet with the owners of ``qualifying facilities,''=
=20
the smaller power generators that provide about one-fourth of the state's=
=20
electrical power.=20
Many of the generators have been either scaling back output or shutting dow=
n=20
entirely, contending that the state's two largest utilities owe them $1.5=
=20
billion.=20
Davis said he expected the power generators to agree to accept partial=20
payment for the energy they've sold the utilities.=20
Larger power generators are owed $5 billion to $15 billion for energy they=
=20
sold to the state and utilities, said Jan Smutny-Jones, executive director =
of=20
the Independent Energy Producers Association.=20
An official with Mirant Corp., which says it is owed $385 million, said he=
=20
was aware of the meeting with Davis, but he did not know the topic.=20
``We're very willing to send someone, if the governor is willing to work wi=
th=20
the generators on a cooperative solution,'' said spokesman Brian O'Neel.=20
Also Monday, Davis said that Pacific Gas & Electric Co. could still be forc=
ed=20
to sell its power transmission lines to the state, even though the utility =
is=20
now under the protection of federal bankruptcy court.=20
Davis had been working on a deal to buy the company's lines. But those talk=
s=20
fell through weeks ago, and on April 6, PG&E filed for Chapter 11 bankruptc=
y=20
protection.=20
Speaking to reporters at a technology conference, Davis said a creditors=20
committee of businesses owed money by PG&E is considering asking the=20
bankruptcy judge to force a sale of the utility's power lines to the state.=
=20
Davis said his advisers met with the committee recently to brief them on=20
talks to buy the transmission lines of financially troubled San Diego Gas &=
=20
Electric Co.=20
The governor would like to take over the state's 32,000-mile power grid so =
he=20
can control the flow of electricity through the state and gain a negotiatin=
g=20
advantage when dealing with power producers.=20
Southern California Edison has already agreed to sell its power lines to th=
e=20
state.=20

Mercury News Staff Writer Steve Johnson contributed to this report.=20

