PG&E lobbied heavily just before bankruptcy=20
Published Tuesday, May 1, 2001, in the San Jose Mercury News=20
BY DION NISSENBAUM=20

Mercury News Sacramento Bureau=20


SACRAMENTO -- In the three months before it declared bankruptcy, Pacific Ga=
s=20
& Electric Co. spent nearly $650,000 lobbying state officials -- about=20
two-thirds of what the company spent all of last year trying to change=20
California laws.=20
The figures, reported Monday to the California secretary of state, offered=
=20
concrete evidence of the aggressive lobbying effort made by the now-bankrup=
t=20
utility to press its case. And it outraged consumer activists and state=20
leaders.=20
``Clearly it confirms that PG&E's priority wasn't keeping rates low,'' said=
=20
Steve Maviglio, spokesman for Gov. Gray Davis. ``They spent more time and=
=20
energy propping up their corporate image than paying attention to=20
California's energy needs.''=20
In all of 2000, when the first signs of the energy crisis appeared, the=20
utility spent about $900,000 lobbying state leaders. In the first three=20
months of 2001, PG&E spent $644,000. Ron Low, a PG&E spokesman, said the=20
spending came in response to hundreds of bills introduced at the special=20
legislative session on the energy crisis called by Davis and hundreds of=20
hours spent in Sacramento talking with state leaders about the company's=20
plight.=20
``The bills and legislation had the potential to impact our customers,'' Lo=
w=20
said. ``We were providing testimony at committees, information requested by=
=20
legislators and doing the analysis required.''=20
In trying to sway California officials, PG&E hired some of the state's most=
=20
prominent lobbyists. Among those enlisted by PG&E were Platinum Advisors, a=
=20
firm headed by former Davis campaign finance adviser Darius Anderson and a=
=20
law firm headed by the chief of staff to former GOP Gov. George Deukmejian.=
=20
PG&E dwarfed other energy interests with its lobbying, but other power=20
companies spent tens of thousands of dollars in Sacramento.=20
San Diego Gas & Electric spent more than $190,000 in the first three months=
=20
of 2001, almost as much as for all of 2000.=20
Southern California Edison, which spent $1.4 million on lobbying last year,=
=20
had not filed its latest report as of Monday night.=20
All three utilities have spent the past year trying to persuade state leade=
rs=20
to rescue them from bankruptcy. During the crisis, the state has stepped in=
=20
to buy energy for the utilities, agreed to raise rates and offered a comple=
x=20
bailout plan.=20
Edison agreed last month to the bailout offer, but PG&E turned down the sam=
e=20
deal and declared bankruptcy April 6.=20


Contact Dion Nissenbaum at dnissenbaum@sjmercury.com or (916) 441-4603.=20
