Cheney outlines energy strategy for U.S.=20
The vice president says California-type blackouts are possible elsewhere.=
=20
May 1, 2001=20
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
The Associated Press=20
TORONTO Vice President Dick Cheney warned Monday that the whole nation coul=
d=20
face California-style blackouts as he outlined a national energy strategy=
=20
relying heavily on oil, coal, natural gas and nuclear-power development - b=
ut=20
not conservation.=20
"The aim here is efficiency, not austerity," Cheney told editors and=20
publishers at The Associated Press annual meeting. The nation cannot "simpl=
y=20
conserve or ration our way out of the situation we're in."=20
In his first extensive remarks about the energy recommendations his=20
Cabinet-level task force will make to Bush by the end of May, Cheney blamed=
=20
current shortages on shortsighted decisions in the past. He said=20
conservation, while perhaps "a sign of personal virtue," does not make for=
=20
sound or comprehensive policy.=20
Saving the specifics for his boss to review and then announce, Cheney=20
promised "a mix of new legislation, some executive action as well as privat=
e=20
initiatives" to cope with rising energy prices and growing demand.=20
He said anew that the administration intends to push for drilling in the=20
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge despite strong congressional opposition.=20
He rejected price controls, tapping the Strategic Petroleum Reserve or=20
creating new bur eaucracies.=20
Over the next two decades, it will take between 1,300 and 1,900 new power=
=20
plants - or one every week for 20 years - just to meet projected increases =
in=20
nationwide demand, Cheney said.=20
Energy shortages in California already have forced rolling blackouts. And h=
e=20
said, "Without a clear, coherent energy strategy for the nation, all=20
Americans could one day go through what Californians are experiencing now, =
or=20
even worse."=20
