Bush taking a supply-side policy on energy=20
Cheney says oil, coal and natural gas will be the primary resources for=20
'years down the road.'=20
May 1, 2001=20
By JOSEPH KAHN
The New York Times=20











WASHINGTON - Vice President Dick Cheney said Monday that oil, coal and=20
natural gas will remain America's primary energy resources for "years down=
=20
the road," and that the Bush administration's energy strategy will aim main=
ly=20
to increase the supply of fossil fuels, rather than limit demand.=20
Cheney, who ran the Dallas-based oil-services company Haliburton Inc. befor=
e=20
becoming vice president, offered a supply-oriented energy philosophy that=
=20
seems likely to dominate the report his task force is expected to issue as=
=20
early as mid-May.=20
The report to President George W. Bush is expected to recommend legislation=
,=20
executive actions and incentives for the private sector.=20
His comments, delivered to the annual meeting of The Associated Press in=20
Toronto, seemed partly a combative response to Democrats and=20
environmentalists who argue that the Bush administration has used=20
California's electricity shortages as a pretext to enact energy policies th=
at=20
have been favored by industry executives for many years.=20
In discussing their energy plans recently, administration officials have pu=
t=20
the most emphasis on opening protected lands to oil and gas exploration,=20
while rolling back environmental rules that inhibit the burning of coal and=
=20
the construction of pipelines and refineries.=20
Bush's most-visible steps to combat what he labeled an energy crisis have=
=20
alienated environmentalists. He rejected a treaty that would reduce emissio=
ns=20
of gases cited as a cause of global warming and backtracked on his own pled=
ge=20
to require controls on greenhouse-gas emissions by power plants, citing=20
urgent energy needs.=20
Cheney said drastic measures were necessary because the needs are so great.=
=20
He estimated that the country needs 38,000 miles of new pipelines to carry=
=20
natural gas, for example.=20
Coal, Cheney said, has been neglected. It is America's "most-plentiful sour=
ce=20
of affordable energy." He said people who seek to phase out its use, largel=
y=20
because they consider it a major source of air pollution, "deny reality."=
=20
He said the most environmentally friendly way to increase energy supplies w=
as=20
to extend the life of existing nuclear plants and grant permits to build ne=
w=20
ones, because they have zero emissions of greenhouse gases.=20
Utility-industry executives have applauded the administration's support of=
=20
nuclear power, but questioned the economic viability of building new nuclea=
r=20
power plants anytime soon. Environmentalists dispute Cheney's contention th=
at=20
nuclear power is the cleanest source of energy because they say the mining=
=20
and enriching of uranium and the storage of nuclear waste are environmental=
=20
hazards.=20
Cheney indicated the administration would put some weight on energy=20
efficiency.=20
New technology - like computer screens that use far less power and=20
energy-efficient light bulbs - have an important role because they can save=
=20
energy without reducing living standards, he said. But he said he would=20
oppose any measure based on the premise that Americans now "live too well" =
or=20
that people should "do more with less."=20
Some people who have talked with administration officials about the=20
forthcoming energy plan expect that the policy will include some tax-relate=
d=20
measures to promote efficiency. Among those considered most likely: Grantin=
g=20
tax credits for people who buy fuel-efficient automobiles and for power=20
companies that produce electricity using renewable energy sources, like=20
solar, wind and geothermal.=20
He said new drilling technologies mean that exploration can take place in t=
he=20
19-million acre refuge, which President Eisenhower made protected federal=
=20
land, without disturbing the habitat for caribou and other wildlife. The=20
affected area totals no more than 2,000 acres, he said, "one-fifth the size=
=20
of Dulles Airport" outside Washington.=20

