Power supplier will pay to settle=20
Regulators to accept $8 million settlement from Williams Cos. over price=20
hikes last year.=20
May 1, 2001=20
By KATE BERRY
The Orange County Register=20
An energy company accused of withholding power to drive up prices in=20
California's electricity market agreed to pay $8 million in a settlement=20
approved Monday by federal energy regulators.=20
The settlement is the first by a company accused of charging excessive=20
electricity prices in the state.=20
The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission accepted the settlement in which=
=20
Williams Cos., of Tulsa, Okla., will refund the state's grid operator $8=20
million for power sold at more than 10 times what it otherwise would have=
=20
cost.=20
The purchases were made in a 10-day period last April and May. Regulators=
=20
said Williams deliberately kept generating units in Long Beach and Huntingt=
on=20
Beach offline to raise prices. The California Independent System Operator,=
=20
which manages the state's electric grid, designated those units to supply=
=20
power during periods of peak demand at contracted prices.=20
The FERC order stated that "Williams had a financial incentive to prolong=
=20
outages," at the two plants, which are owned by AES Corp.=20
Williams would have been paid $63 a megawatt hour if the two power plants h=
ad=20
been online, the FERC order stated. Instead, the company was paid $750 a=20
megawatt hour for electricity from other AES generating units during that=
=20
period.=20
AES had said the units were taken offline for repairs. AES, which sells all=
=20
power generated at its three plants in Southern California to Williams unde=
r=20
a contract, did not share in the profits from the power sales.=20
Officials at Williams have repeatedly denied that the units were deliberate=
ly=20
shut down. As part of the settlement, the company did not admit wrongdoing.=
=20
Federal officials had required Williams and AES to justify more than $40=20
million charged to the ISO. The companies faced paying a maximum of $10.8=
=20
million in refunds.=20
In a separate matter, Williams is one of several power providers accused by=
=20
federal regulators of overcharging the ISO $124 million for power in Januar=
y=20
and February. The power providers are still disputing those charges.=20

