Energy notebook: Bills target high natural-gas prices=20
State measures aim to boost production, speed OKs on new storage tanks and=
=20
order tariff review.=20
May 1, 2001=20
From Register news services=20
SACRAMENTO California lawmakers introduced measures intended to lower the=
=20
price of natural gas, which has been as much as 10 times higher in the stat=
e=20
than in other parts of the country.=20
The four measures, introduced by members of the state Assembly, would speed=
=20
up the approval of underground gas-storage tanks, encourage the production =
of=20
natural gas for industrial uses, and order the review of tariffs relating t=
o=20
natural gas.=20
"This market has gone out of control," said Joe Canciamilla, chairman of th=
e=20
Assembly's subcommittee on natural gas and author of two of the bills=20
introduced Monday.=20
Almost 80 percent of electricity produced in California is generated by=20
burning natural gas. High electricity prices in the state, which have led t=
o=20
the near insolvency of California's two largest electric utilities, have be=
en=20
blamed partly on high natural-gas prices.=20
PG&E Corp.'s Pacific Gas & Electric, the state's No. 1 electric utility,=20
filed for bankruptcy protection this month after running up $9 billion in=
=20
power-buying losses. Edison International's Southern California Edison, the=
=20
state's second largest utility, also is on the verge of bankruptcy after=20
accruing more than $5.4 billion in power losses.=20
Under the state's deregulation laws, wholesale power prices have been allow=
ed=20
to float, while consumer rates have been temporarily frozen.=20
AB78X, by Canciamilla, a Democrat from Pittsburg, would streamline the=20
approval of new underground tanks so more natural gas could be stored in=20
California and demand for gas from out of state would be smoothed out. AB23=
X=20
directs the Public Utilities Commission to review all natural-gas tariffs.=
=20
AB73X, co-sponsored by Canciamilla, would allow natural gas unfit for use i=
n=20
residences to be sold to industrial customers. AB42X reduces to one year fr=
om=20
as much as two years the permitting process for pipeline construction.=20
Regulators mull surcharge to help pay off generators=20
WASHINGTON U.S. energy regulators are considering whether to force=20
California's electricity grid operator to impose a surcharge on power sales=
=20
to pay for more than $14 billion owed to generators by California utilities=
.=20
The proposal is part of the price mitigation order for California issued by=
=20
the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission last Wednesday. The public can=20
comment on the proposal for 30 days before the commission decides whether t=
o=20
implement it.=20
The Edison Electric Institute, an industry group, cautiously supported the=
=20
idea. "We're in favor of anything that keeps the lights on in California,"=
=20
said spokeswoman Pat McMurray. "Anything that keeps the generators selling=
=20
into California is good," she said, adding that the group had yet to study=
=20
the proposal carefully.=20
The FERC is proposing that an unspecified surcharge be placed in an escrow=
=20
account by the California Independent System Operator to ensure that=20
generators are paid. Whether the surcharge would be applied toward past bil=
ls=20
or future power bills is open for debate, according to the order.=20
California utilities have amassed billions of dollars in debt buying=20
wholesale power at high prices while being limited by law as to what they c=
an=20
charge consumers. The state is preparing to sell $10 billion in bonds to pa=
y=20
for electricity this summer, when blackouts are expected as demand exceeds=
=20
supplies.=20
Jan Smutny-Jones, executive director of the Independent Energy Producers=20
Association, said his group is still "trying to sort out how something like=
=20
that might work," but offered no further comment.=20
There is also a question whether the FERC has jurisdiction to order the=20
California ISO to collect the surcharge, said Edison Electric Institute=20
spokeswoman McMurray, adding that the issue may have to be clarified later.=
=20
PG&E still may sell its transmission lines to state=20
SAN FRANCISCO California's largest utility still may sell its transmission=
=20
lines to the state despite seeking bankruptcy protection when an earlier de=
al=20
with state negotiators fell through, Gov. Gray Davis said Monday.=20
Davis told reporters that a creditors committee of businesses owed money by=
=20
Pacific Gas and Electric Co. asked state negotiators for a briefing on talk=
s=20
to buy the transmission lines of financially troubled San Diego Gas and=20
Electric Co., whose parent company is Sempra Energy.=20
"The creditors committee called us and asked for a briefing on Sempra last=
=20
week," Davis said, adding he believes there is some possibility of buying=
=20
PG&E's lines. "It helps us because it helps get PG&E back in."=20
PG&E did not immediately return calls for comment.=20
The utility filed for Chapter 11 protection April 6 after failed attempts b=
y=20
the state to buy its transmission lines to help the troubled utility pull=
=20
itself out of a multi-billion dollar debt.=20
The governor struck a $3.5 billion deal with Southern California Edison Co.=
=20
for its lines, undeveloped land and the promise of relatively cheap power.=
=20
The deal requires legislative approval. The state has offered $1 billion to=
=20
Sempra Energy for a similar package.=20
Davis told a crowd at investment firm J.P. Morgan's H&Q Technology Conferen=
ce=20
that his state is boosting spending on technology research and education=20
incentives to keep California attractive to investment.=20
In other news:=20
The state paid nearly $90 million to buy electricity on each of a couple of=
=20
days last week as Californians turned up their air conditioning amid=20
unseasonably warm temperatures, according to state finance officials.=20
That amount is double what the state had been paying for a day's worth of=
=20
power earlier this year, but only a slight increase from the $73 million it=
=20
has been paying recently since the Pacific Gas & Electricity Co. bankruptcy=
=20
filing.=20
Also on Friday, state finance officers asked for an additional $500 million=
=20
from the legislature to buy power. That brings the total amount that the=20
state has set aside for electricity since January to $6.2 billion.=20
A federal judge dismissed a lawsuit Monday filed by Duke Energy against Gov=
.=20
Gray Davis over energy contracts the state seized earlier this year from=20
Southern California Edison and Pacific Gas & Electric.=20
U.S. District Court Judge Terry Hatter ruled that Davis has immunity under=
=20
the 11th Amendment, which prevents residents of one state from suing the=20
government of another state in federal court.=20
The Associated Press and Bloomberg News contributed to this report.=20

