Tuesday, May 1, 2001=20






Leadership blackout
Gov. Davis seems unplugged in dealing with the crisis=20
April 29, 2001
By Steven Greenhut
The Orange County Register
We've seen it a bazillion times on TV and in the movies. A crisis threatens=
 a=20
family, a community, a nation. Perhaps the threat comes from an enemy durin=
g=20
wartime. Or from a gang of criminals, corporate polluters, corrupt governme=
nt=20
officials or aliens from Mars.=20
Out of nowhere, someone - sometimes from the least expected place - steps t=
o=20
the plate. It's not just in the movies. History books are filled with the=
=20
likes of George Washington, Winston Churchill, Lech Walesa. People who seiz=
ed=20
the moment and made it their own; people who chose to lead - and worry abou=
t=20
the consequences later.
History books are filled, also, with those who ducked for cover, pointed=20
fingers or ran away.
No one would have believed it, but in spring 2001 the nation's most populou=
s=20
state is struggling with looming blackouts, soaring electricity rates, stat=
e=20
legislators blustering about Evil Power Producers and proposing "solutions"=
=20
that lost credence when the Berlin Wall fell. And rather than lead, the man=
=20
on the hot seat has become angry, immobile. He stands there, yelling "It's=
=20
not my fault," and waiting for the mess to evaporate.
Most Californians sympathize with Gov. Gray Davis, who just a few months ag=
o=20
was viewed as an inevitable presidential contender. We know he didn't creat=
e=20
the current mess.
But it's Davis' moment, nonetheless. One would have thought the man who spe=
nt=20
his career plotting his rise to the governor's office would have had some=
=20
underlying reason for aspiring to the post. Anyone can be a leader when=20
there's nothing to do but spend a surplus. But the real test comes when the=
=20
chips are down.
No one should pin their hopes on politicians. Typically, pols should tend t=
o=20
the administrative affairs of government and let a free people live free=20
lives. But the electricity imbroglio is a government-created mess that=20
initially requires a government solution.
After all, we're talking about highly regulated utilities. It is a botched=
=20
state de-regulation plan - actually a re-regulation plan - that exacerbated=
=20
the energy problems. And it has been the state's unwillingness to allow pow=
er=20
generators to build plants that has added to supply shortfalls.
There are two directions to choose: Toward a system owned and operated by t=
he=20
state government, or toward a market-based system that treats electricity=
=20
like any other commodity. The price of natural gas, food, clothing and othe=
r=20
essentials are allowed to rise and fall, according to the marketplace.
Why is electricity so holy?
If prices are allowed to float, and generators are allowed to provide the=
=20
juice to fill demand, soon enough a competitive market will overtake the=20
initial price jumps and force prices down again. Sen. Tom McClintock,=20
R-Thousand Oaks, one of the few rational voices in Sacramento, argues that=
=20
Davis should have returned the surplus to taxpayers, who would have then ha=
d=20
the means to pay for the initial price spikes.
Instead, Davis has spent the surplus buying electricity, allowing taxpayers=
=20
to foot the bill because he refuses to allow customers (Aren't they the sam=
e=20
people?) to pay market prices. Adding insult to injury, he refuses to make=
=20
his dealings public.
Furthermore, Davis could have stabilized the situation last year when leade=
rs=20
of the state's utilities tried in vain to get his attention about looming=
=20
problems and to urge limited price increases and use of long-term contracts=
=20
to buy power. Instead, Davis and his handpicked political crony who runs th=
e=20
Public Utilities Commission did nothing - except let a problem spiral into =
a=20
full-blown crisis.=20
Without any leadership from the top, Californians hear a cacophony of=20
proposals from below.
The Legislature, dominated by Democrats far out on the "left-wing yahoo"=20
scale, are talking about Texas power generators in the same overheated=20
rhetoric some right-wingers use to talk about the Chinese communists. One=
=20
talked about sending tanks to Houston.
Understandably, the utility companies are looking out for their own=20
interests.=20
Pacific Gas & Electric, angry that the governor refused to do anything abou=
t=20
the crisis, declared bankruptcy the day after Davis' say-nothing address to=
=20
Californians this month. As some commentators note, PG&E is far more=20
comfortable dealing with a bankruptcy judge than dealing with a governor an=
d=20
legislators who starred in "Clueless in Sacramento."
By contrast, Southern California Edison has chosen not to file bankruptcy=
=20
now, preferring instead to sell the state its transmission lines as a way t=
o=20
generate cash to keep this quasi-private entity going.=20
John Bryson, a longtime Davis associate and a creature of the=20
government/regulatory/utility model, frankly admits that the main rationale=
=20
for selling the lines to the state is to keep his company afloat, independe=
nt=20
and credit worthy.
But it's a lousy idea for taxpayers, who would gain a multibillion-dollar=
=20
liability badly in need of costly maintenance. I don't blame Bryson (who, b=
y=20
the way, co-founded the left-wing Natural Resources Defense Council early i=
n=20
his career) for looking out for his company first. But what's good for the=
=20
utilities is not necessarily good for taxpayers.
Then there are the self-proclaimed consumer advocates. Their goal seems to =
be=20
to destroy the utilities so bureaucrats can run the system. These are peopl=
e=20
who believe markets are the spawn of Satan.
Republicans have generally been content to let Davis twist in the wind, whi=
ch=20
isn't the best leadership model, either. Sen. McClintock and a few others=
=20
have offered meaty ideas. But they are a minority of a minority and have no=
=20
real political muscle in the Democrat-dominated statehouse.
Who is left? Who you gonna call? Who is going to keep the still-thriving=20
California economy from going south?
The answer is Gray Davis. It's his hour, his moment, his crisis. The answer=
s=20
are out there if only this "pragmatic" and "centrist" governor would be=20
willing to look to the market rather than the government. (Hint: See=20
solutions outlined on these pages today.)
It's time to stop delaying, blustering, blaming others. It's time for Davis=
=20
to remind Californians why they elected him governor. Steven Greenhut is an=
=20
Orange County Register editorial writer.=20

