National Desk; Section A=20
CHENEY PROMOTES INCREASING SUPPLY AS ENERGY POLICY=20
By JOSEPH KAHN=20
?=20
05/01/2001=20
The New York Times=20
Page 1, Column 6=20
c. 2001 New York Times Company=20
WASHINGTON, April 30 -- Vice President Dick Cheney said today that oil, coa=
l=20
and natural gas would remain the United States' primary energy resources fo=
r=20
''years down the road'' and that the Bush administration's energy strategy=
=20
would aim mainly to increase supply of fossil fuels, rather than limit=20
demand.=20
In his most comprehensive comments to date on the energy task force he is=
=20
heading on behalf of President Bush, Mr. Cheney dismissed as 1970's-era=20
thinking the notion that ''we could simply conserve or ration our way out''=
=20
of what he called an energy crisis.=20
The only solution, he said, is a government-backed push to find new domesti=
c=20
sources of oil and gas, including in protected areas of the Arctic National=
=20
Wildlife Refuge, and an all-out drive to build power plants -- a need that =
he=20
says will require one new electricity-generating plant a week for 20 years.=
=20
''America's reliance on energy, and fossil fuels in particular, has lately=
=20
taken on an urgency not felt since the late 1970's,'' Mr. Cheney said.=20
''Without a clear, coherent energy strategy, all Americans could one day go=
=20
through what Californians are experiencing now, or worse.''=20
Mr. Cheney, who ran the oil-services company Halliburton Inc. before becomi=
ng=20
vice president, offered a supply-oriented energy philosophy that seems like=
ly=20
to dominate the report the cabinet-level task force is expected to issue as=
=20
early as mid-May. The report is expected to recommend legislation, executiv=
e=20
actions and incentives for the private sector.=20
The vice president's comments, delivered to the annual meeting of The=20
Associated Press in Toronto, seemed partly a combative response to Democrat=
s=20
and environmentalists who argue that the Bush administration has used=20
California's electricity shortages as a pretext to enact energy policies th=
at=20
have been favored by industry executives for many years.=20
In discussing their energy plans recently, administration officials have pu=
t=20
the most emphasis on opening protected lands to oil and gas exploration,=20
while rolling back environmental rules that inhibit the burning of coal and=
=20
the construction of pipelines and refineries. They have also strongly=20
advocated the use of nuclear power.=20
Critics have faulted the administration for moving quickly to abandon a=20
treaty on global warming and rejecting controls on carbon dioxide emissions=
=20
from power plants, steps Mr. Bush said were vital because of energy=20
shortages. The administration has also come under withering criticism for=
=20
delaying stricter standards on arsenic in drinking water.=20
Mr. Cheney said today that environmentalists had taken things too far. He=
=20
said a recent television advertisement showing a child asking for more=20
arsenic in her water was a ''cheap shot.''=20
Drastic measures to increase energy supplies are justified, he said, becaus=
e=20
the geometry of supply and demand curves are so alarming. He estimated that=
=20
the country needed 38,000 miles of new pipelines to carry natural gas,=20
covering the distance of Maine to California more than 12 times over.=20
Coal, Mr. Cheney said, has been neglected. It is the United States' ''most=
=20
plentiful source of affordable energy.'' He said people who sought to phase=
=20
out its use, largely because they considered it a major source of air=20
pollution, ''deny reality.''=20
He said the most environmentally friendly way to increase energy supplies w=
as=20
to extend the life of existing nuclear plants and grant permits to build ne=
w=20
ones, because they had no emissions of greenhouse gases.=20
''We can safeguard the environment by making greater use of the cleanest=20
methods of power generation we know,'' he said, speaking of nuclear power.=
=20
''If we are serious about environmental protection, then we must seriously=
=20
question the wisdom of backing away from what is, as a matter of record, a=
=20
safe, clean and very plentiful energy source.''=20
Utility industry executives have applauded the administration's support of=
=20
nuclear power, but questioned the economic viability of building new nuclea=
r=20
power plants anytime soon. Environmentalists dispute Mr. Cheney's contentio=
n=20
that nuclear power is the cleanest source of energy because they say the=20
mining and enriching of uranium and the storage of nuclear waste are hazard=
s.=20
Mr. Cheney indicated that the administration would put some emphasis on=20
energy efficiency. New technology -- like computer screens that use far les=
s=20
power and energy-efficient light bulbs -- have an important role because th=
ey=20
can save energy without reducing living standards, he said. But he said he=
=20
would oppose any measure based on the premise that Americans now ''live too=
=20
well'' or that people should ''do more with less.''=20
''The aim here is efficiency, not austerity,'' he said. ''Conservation may =
be=20
a sign of personal virtue, but it is not a sufficient basis for a sound,=20
comprehensive energy policy.''=20
Some people who have talked with administration officials about the energy=
=20
plan expect that the policy will include some tax-related measures to promo=
te=20
efficiency. Among those considered most likely are tax credits for people w=
ho=20
buy fuel-efficient automobiles and for power companies that produce=20
electricity using renewable energy sources.=20
But the budget Mr. Bush submitted to Congress in early April sharply reduce=
d=20
spending by the Department of Energy on research and development for energy=
=20
efficiency and renewable energy technologies.=20
''They give lip service to efficiency, but their whole emphasis is on=20
supply,'' said Senator Jeff Bingaman, a New Mexico Democrat who has=20
introduced energy legislation that he says strikes a finer balance between=
=20
increasing supply and controlling demand.=20
In a report to be released later this week, the American Council for an=20
Energy-Efficient Economy estimates that raising the fuel efficiency of cars=
=20
and light trucks by what it calls a modest amount could do far more to redu=
ce=20
reliance on imported oil than drilling for oil in the Arctic National=20
Wildlife Refuge.=20
Fuel economy standards reached their peak in 1988, when the average passeng=
er=20
vehicle covered 26 miles on a gallon of gas. The average fell to 24 miles p=
er=20
gallon last year, because more Americans drive light trucks, which have low=
er=20
mandated efficiency standards than cars.=20
Raising average fuel use by cars and light trucks to 35 miles per gallon by=
=20
2010 would result in oil savings of 1.5 million barrels a day by that time,=
=20
the report says. The United States Geological Survey estimates that the=20
Alaskan refuge would probably produce 580,000 barrels a day later this=20
decade.=20
Mr. Cheney did not discuss the merits of raising government-mandated=20
Corporate Average Fuel Economy standards in his address today. But he=20
strongly defended the administration's proposal to allow drilling for oil a=
nd=20
gas in the Alaskan refuge.=20
The administration has sent mixed signals recently on how hard it intends t=
o=20
push to open the refuge. Christie Whitman, the Environmental Protection=20
Agency administrator, said earlier this month that the energy plan would no=
t=20
emphasize drilling in the Alaskan wilderness, but other officials=20
contradicted her.=20
Mr. Cheney left little doubt of his support. He said new oil-drilling=20
technologies meant that exploration could take place in the 19-million-acre=
=20
refuge without disturbing wildlife. The affected area totals no more than=
=20
2,000 acres, he said, ''one-fifth the size of Dulles Airport.''=20

Photo: Vice President Dick Cheney said yesterday in Toronto that the=20
administration's energy policy would support more nuclear plants.=20
(Reuters)(pg. A20)=20

