National Desk; Section A=20
River's Power Aids California And Enriches the Northwest=20
By BLAINE HARDEN=20
?=20
05/01/2001=20
The New York Times=20
Page 1, Column 5=20
c. 2001 New York Times Company=20
GEORGE, Wash. -- Doing something nice for California has never been a=20
priority here in the Columbia River Basin, where high-voltage power lines=
=20
lope across irrigated fields of alfalfa, potatoes and wheat.=20
Politicians from California, as farmers in this area will explain at great=
=20
length, have been scheming for decades to siphon off the basin's cheap=20
electricity and water.=20
Californians, however, have been noticeably less irritating as of late.=20
Having fouled up electricity deregulation six ways from Sunday, they are=20
skidding into the summer air-conditioning season desperately short of power=
.=20
In the last year, much of their salvation has come from the Columbia River,=
=20
whose monstrous dams are the largest hydroelectricity machines in North=20
America.=20
All along the river, from Portland, Ore., to British Columbia, utility=20
companies, aluminum makers and farmers have joined to help save California =
--=20
but at a staggering price. Charging whatever California's dysfunctional pow=
er=20
market will bear, people in this narrow stretch of the Northwest have creat=
ed=20
a kind of Kuwait along the Columbia.=20
With their record profits, some public utilities are wiring the emptiness o=
f=20
Eastern Washington with fiber optics, buying diesel generators to make stil=
l=20
more power and paying Wall Street-style wages to electricity traders -- whi=
le=20
making sure that their electricity rates remain among the cheapest in North=
=20
America. Just north of the border in British Columbia, a state-owned utilit=
y=20
luxuriated in its California windfall by mailing out rebate checks to 1.6=
=20
million customers.=20
Their good fortune, though, has come with a measure of ambivalence and may=
=20
well be short-lived. A severe drought is already hurting farmers across the=
=20
region. If it continues, utilities along the river will have to buy power a=
nd=20
may be punished by the same market forces that gave them a windfall.=20
''This is not nice money,'' said Alice Parker, a retired farmer who heads a=
=20
group that promotes irrigation in the Columbia Basin. ''It is something tha=
t=20
is offered to us not to use water so Californians can run their=20
air-conditioners.''=20
Nice or not, a whole lot of money flooded into the Columbia Basin.=20
North of here in sparsely populated Chelan County, a publicly owned utility=
=20
that has two dams on the Columbia made three times as much money last year=
=20
than it ever had before. With just 35,000 local customers, the utility last=
=20
year had a $58.2 million profit. It paid its two top power traders $285,000=
=20
each, an astonishing income in a county where per capita income is less tha=
n=20
$25,000 a year. The utility refuses to reveal the traders' names for fear=
=20
their children might be kidnapped.=20
The chief operating officer of Chelan County Public Utility District=20
acknowledged that increases in the cost of power were ''huge'' and=20
''obscene.'' But the executive, Charles J. Hosken, added, ''We would be=20
imprudent if we did not maximize this market for our customer owners.''=20
Next door in equally sparse Grant County, a public utility that also owns t=
wo=20
dams on the Columbia has made even more money maximizing the market. It had=
 a=20
record $88.8 million in profits last year -- more than double its best=20
previous year.=20
Grant County Public Utility District, which has just 40,000 retail customer=
s,=20
is using its windfall to help build a $70 million fiber optic network for=
=20
local residents. It has also bought 20 diesel generators to guard against=
=20
power shortages and, if possible, exploit the power gold-rush. The utility=
=20
estimates that those generators could add $50 million to profits in the=20
coming year.=20
Like Chelan, Grant is using its profits as a kind of drought insurance to=
=20
insulate its customers from high market prices for electricity, when, as no=
w,=20
local needs exceed generating capacity in the river. Power rates in Grant a=
nd=20
Chelan Counties are about one-fifth as much as in New York City.=20
Grant County's utility has rejected, for the time being, the idea of giving=
 a=20
share of its profits to its customers.=20
''How would it look if Grant County gives away rebates while so many people=
=20
are paying more for electricity?'' asked Lon Topaz, director of resource=20
management for the utility. ''It would be lousy politics.''=20
An Upside-Down Economy=20
The second-worst drought on record in the Columbia River Basin has combined=
=20
with California's deregulation mess to further distort the energy market.=
=20
Drought has not only helped increase the price at which electricity can be=
=20
sold on the spot market -- 10 to 20 times as much as last year's price -- i=
t=20
has strengthened a compelling bottom-line rationale for conservation. Every=
=20
megawatt not purchased and used in the Northwest (often at locked-in,=20
long-term prices that are a fraction of the current market rate) can be sen=
t=20
south to California. For many utilities, conservation spells local savings=
=20
and a long-distance bonanza.=20
As a result, a regional economy built on half a century of cheap hydropower=
=20
has been stood on its head. Irrigation farmers here are being paid up to $4=
40=20
an acre not to farm.=20
Similarly, aluminum companies are collecting about $1.7 billion this year b=
y=20
not making aluminum. Companies like Alcoa have earned profits that delight=
=20
Wall Street, while keeping about 10,000 workers on their payroll, by=20
reselling hydropower that they bought in the mid-1990's under a cheap=20
long-term contract.=20
Even residential customers are being offered a chance to make a few dollars=
=20
from the power crunch. Avista Utilities has announced that it will pay its=
=20
customers in Washington and Idaho 5 cents for every kilowatt they do not us=
e,=20
if their consumption falls more than 5 percent below last year's level.=20
For utilities in the Northwest, by far the largest profits from California'=
s=20
electricity crisis have been secured in British Columbia. A number of priva=
te=20
American utilities have also benefited from California's troubles.=20
BC Hydro, a utility owned by British Columbia with dams on the Columbia and=
=20
Peace Rivers, is the first corporation in the history of the province to=20
exceed $1 billion in profits, as measured in Canadian currency ($712 millio=
n=20
in United States currency).=20
To celebrate, the provincial government ordered BC Hydro to do something it=
=20
had never done before. The utility mailed each of its customers a check for=
=20
$130. BC Hydro also guaranteed them no increases in electricity rates, whic=
h=20
have not gone up for seven years.=20
''We are just happy to be lucky that we have reservoirs and dams that were=
=20
built by people of great foresight,'' said Brian R. D. Smith, chairman of B=
C=20
Hydro.=20
When reminded that a March study by the California Independent System=20
Operator, which runs that state's power grid, accused BC Hydro of market=20
manipulation and profit gouging, Mr. Smith was less happy.=20
''All they do is scream and shout and they won't pay you the money they owe=
=20
you,'' he said, arguing that his company has gone out of its way to help=20
California in its hour of need. Gouging has nothing to do with it, he said,=
=20
adding that it was California's ''awful mess'' in deregulating power market=
s=20
that fueled BC Hydro's record profits.=20
A Good Deal for Farmers=20
In the beginning, that is to say when federal money began transforming the=
=20
Columbia from the world's premier salmon highway into a chain of adjustable=
=20
lakes, no one paid much attention to electricity. The river possessed a thi=
rd=20
of America's hydroelectric potential, but there were not enough people in t=
he=20
Northwest to use more than a fraction of it, and long-distance high-voltage=
=20
transmission lines did not exist.=20
The main intention, when New Deal dollars began raining on the Northwest in=
=20
the 1930's, was to create family farms. Grand Coulee Dam, the biggest dam i=
n=20
North America and by far the largest hydroelectric plant, was primarily=20
designed as a water-delivery device for farmers.=20
Since then, as 6,000 miles of tunnels and concrete canals were built to=20
shuttle water around in sagebrush country, each 960-acre farm in the Columb=
ia=20
Basin Federal Irrigation Project was blessed with at least $2.1 million in=
=20
federal infrastructure subsidies, according to the Bureau of Reclamation,=
=20
which built it.=20
In addition, farmers are guaranteed access to cheap water from the Columbia=
=20
and the right to buy all the electricity they needed to pump that water out=
=20
of the river -- at $1.50 a megawatt. A megawatt of electricity currently=20
sells for $375 to $400 on the spot market. As Paul Pitzer, a Columbia Basin=
=20
historian, has written, farmers here have always felt that ''no price is to=
o=20
high to pay for their water so long as someone else is paying the bill.''=
=20
This year, though, the price finally became unbearably high for the=20
Bonneville Power Administration, a nonprofit agency that markets electricit=
y=20
from 29 federal dams on river. The agency calculated that if it could=20
persuade farmers in the project not to irrigate 90,000 acres of land, water=
=20
left in the Columbia would produce electricity worth as much as $129 millio=
n=20
(if it had to be purchased at current market prices).=20
In a buyout that is without precedent in the Pacific Northwest, Bonneville =
is=20
paying 800 farmers a total of $30 million. The farmers receive $330 for eac=
h=20
acre they do not farm. On top of that, Grant County's public utility is=20
paying many of the same farmers about $100 an acre not to farm their land.=
=20
On April 13, about 20 irrigators gathered for lunch at the Martha Inn Cafe=
=20
here in George to discuss the buyout. Since farm prices are low this year,=
=20
they agreed that it was a good deal.=20
Still, the farmers, who do not like to be reminded of the federal subsidies=
=20
that keep their irrigation system afloat, said they worried about the=20
precedent they set when they traded water for cash.=20
''This has to be a temporary deal,'' said Tom Flynt, 52, who normally farms=
=20
900 acres but has taken 150 acres out of production because of the buyout.=
=20
''If anybody thought this would affect their water rights, there would be n=
o=20
takers.''=20
Several farmers said they did not like the idea of their water supporting t=
he=20
lifestyles of urban people, especially Californians, who, those who were=20
interviewed said, do not appreciate the food that the farmers put on their=
=20
table.=20
''We feel that Americans are making decisions with their mouths full,'' sai=
d=20
Tricia C. Lubach, a marketing consultant whose husband is an irrigation=20
farmer. ''Not too long ago they didn't worry about where the power comes=20
from. Someday they may think about where the food comes from.''=20
A 'Wonderful Energy Fit'=20
A couple of hundred miles northwest of George, in a penthouse conference ro=
om=20
that overlooks Vancouver harbor, Mr. Smith, the chairman of British=20
Columbia's most profitable company, explained in mid-April what a pain it w=
as=20
selling electricity to Californians.=20
''People say to me what are you doing selling power to those ungrateful=20
Californians,'' he said. It does not help, he added, that the state is behi=
nd=20
on its bills by about $300 million.=20
Still, neither BC Hydro nor the provincial government can afford to lose=20
California's money. The utility has become a cash cow for the provincial=20
budget, which in the last decade has received more than $3.7 billion from B=
C=20
Hydro.=20
''We have a wonderful energy fit,'' Mr. Smith said, referring to BC Hydro's=
=20
power-trading relationship with California, if not to Californians=20
themselves. ''We have oversupply in the summer when they have got high=20
demand, and we have got undersupply in the winter when they have got stuff =
to=20
give to us.''=20
BC Hydro has acknowledged that it massages its hydropower system to sell=20
power when it is most needed -- and most expensive -- in California. The=20
utility closes the faucets on its dams at night during the summer, storing=
=20
water while meeting local electricity needs with cheap off-peak power broug=
ht=20
from across the West. In the morning, when prices peak, it opens the faucet=
s=20
and zaps electricity off to California.=20
''We spill water during the day,'' Mr. Smith said. ''Why? Is it because we=
=20
can make more money? No. It's because that is when everybody wants=20
electricity, for God's sake.''=20
Questions about profit gouging on the part of dam-dependent utilities in th=
e=20
Northwest may soon be moot. Drought has reduced the Columbia River runoff s=
o=20
far this year to about half of what is considered normal.=20
The shortfall dovetails with higher costs for natural-gas-fired power plant=
s=20
and a growing gap on the West Coast between demand for electricity and=20
capacity to generate it.=20
''Absent being successful in getting loads down, we could be looking at=20
quadrupling of the power rates,'' said Paul Norman, head of power operation=
s=20
at Bonneville.=20
Unless conservation increases or the drought eases, Mr. Norman warned that =
by=20
late summer, the Northwest's era of cheap power could come to a sudden and=
=20
painfully expensive end.=20

Photo: Electricity generated by Rock Island Dam in Chelan County, Wash.,=20
helped the county's public utility earn a record $58.2 million in profits=
=20
last year. (Larry Davis for The New York Times)(pg. A20) Graph: ''The Publi=
c=20
Utilities'' NET OPERATING PROFITS Graph tracks operating profits since 1995=
