A Section=20
Bush Energy Plan Will Emphasize Production; Cheney: Conservation Is Part of=
=20
Effort=20
Mike Allen=20
?=20
05/01/2001=20
The Washington Post=20
FINAL=20
Page A01=20
Copyright 2001, The Washington Post Co. All Rights Reserved=20
TORONTO, April 30 -- Vice President Cheney said today that the Bush=20
administration's energy policy will emphasize increased generation over=20
conservation and rely on an ambitious expansion of the country's oil, coal=
=20
and natural gas industries in addition to a broader reliance on nuclear=20
power.=20
Providing a preview of the recommendations the administration's energy task=
=20
force will make to President Bush in the next few weeks, Cheney said he see=
s=20
no "quick fixes" to the problems that have led to rolling blackouts in=20
California and forecasts of higher gasoline prices for motorists this summe=
r.=20
"The potential crisis we face is largely the result of short-sighted domest=
ic=20
policies -- or, as in recent years, no policy at all," Cheney told editors=
=20
and publishers at the Associated Press's annual meeting. "As a country, we=
=20
have demanded more and more energy. But we have not brought online the=20
supplies needed to meet that demand."=20
He said 1,300 to 1,900 new power plants will be needed over the next 20=20
years.=20
Cheney, who is heading the task force that has been meeting in private sinc=
e=20
January, provided few details of the panel's conclusions. He said it would=
=20
recommend "a mix of new legislation, some executive action as well as priva=
te=20
initiatives" to bolster energy production.=20
But he made clear that the administration will base its policy on promoting=
 a=20
vigorous expansion of the traditional energy industry and will avoid the=20
kinds of austerity measures that marked the country's response to the energ=
y=20
crisis in the 1970s.=20
"To speak exclusively of conservation is to duck the tough issues," Cheney=
=20
said. "Conservation may be a sign of personal virtue, but it is not a=20
sufficient basis -- all by itself -- for a sound, comprehensive energy=20
policy."=20
Cheney said alternative energy sources such as wind and solar power may=20
provide an important part of the country's energy strategy in the years to=
=20
come but that it is premature to rely on them now. "Years down the road,=20
alternative fuels may become a great deal more plentiful," he said. "But we=
=20
are not yet in any position to stake our economy and our own way of life on=
=20
that possibility."=20
Bush promised during last year's campaign to develop a muscular national=20
energy strategy, and named Cheney to head the task force less than two week=
s=20
after taking office. Various sectors of the energy industry have billions o=
f=20
dollars riding on the outcome of the administration's policy review.=20
Cheney said the plan will call for increased exploration for new sources of=
=20
oil, coal and natural gas, and construction of refineries, plants and=20
pipelines. He reiterated the administration's support for drilling in=20
Alaska's Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, which he said could be tapped for=
=20
oil without disrupting its environment.=20
Cheney, who was chairman of the oil services firm Halliburton Co. before=20
taking office, called coal "the most plentiful source of affordable energy =
in=20
the country" and said it will remain the nation's primary source of=20
electricity for years.=20
"Coal is not the cleanest source of energy," Cheney said, "and we must=20
support efforts to improve clean-coal technology to soften its impact on th=
e=20
environment."=20
The vice president called nuclear power one of "the cleanest methods of pow=
er=20
generation that we know."=20
"But the government has not granted a single new nuclear power permit in mo=
re=20
than 20 years," Cheney said. "If we're serious about environmental=20
protection, then we must seriously question the wisdom of backing away from=
=20
what is, as a matter of record, a safe, clean and very plentiful energy=20
source."=20
Officials with the coal and nuclear power industries, which have had little=
=20
to celebrate in recent years, welcomed Cheney's remarks.=20
"Bless his heart," said Bill Raney, president of the West Virginia Coal=20
Association. "We have been something of the whipping child for some time no=
w.=20
This is kind of like your dad when he compliments you when you were growing=
=20
up. We've got people in Washington talking to us now."=20
Steve Kerekes, a spokesman for the Nuclear Energy Institute, said it was=20
"heartening to see that the administration is not only recognizing but=20
publicly acknowledging the positive role that nuclear energy plays in a=20
diverse portfolio of energy sources."=20
Several environmental groups said the policy outlined by Cheney could negat=
e=20
whatever good will the administration had gained with its recent spate of=
=20
environmentally friendly announcements. Philip E. Clapp, president of the=
=20
National Environmental Trust, called Cheney's prescription "an=20
across-the-board attack on the environment."=20
Lois Corbett, executive director of the Toronto Energy Alliance, said: "I'd=
=20
hate to think we'll have to throw up a huge iron curtain to keep American=
=20
smog and acid rain on the American side. Clean-coal technology is an=20
oxymoron. It's a dirty fuel."=20
Raney and other coal industry officials were summoned to an administration=
=20
briefing last week in which Energy Secretary Spencer Abraham and other=20
administration officials promised that coal would be a key part of the ener=
gy=20
policy.=20
Attendees said that although no specifics were discussed about tax breaks o=
r=20
relaxed regulations, they were assured the administration would work for a=
=20
more stable and predictable process of getting permits to build or renovate=
=20
coal-fired generating plants.=20
Administration officials said Bush's budget includes $150 million for=20
developing clean-coal technology, new methods for converting coal to energy=
=20
that result in less pollution. Cheney called conservation "an important par=
t=20
of the total effort."=20

Contact: http://www.washingtonpost.com=20
