Western Dreaming -- a buyer's cartel 5/1/01




By Kathleen McFall
kmcfall@ftenergy.com
In California, the cost of electricity was $7 billion in 1999, $32 billion=
=20
last year, and if expectations hold true, will rise to $65 billion this yea=
r,=20
said California Sen. Dianne Feinstein recently. As a consequence of this=20
escalation, the pressure is mounting on state and federal legislators to=20
solve the California crisis=01*or to find someone else to blame it on. It's=
=20
increasingly looking like political suicide to do nothing.

Initiatives and insults are flying, and the only consensus in this=20
politically charged debate is that Western states are facing a grim summer,=
=20
and merchant power companies=01*an easy target=01*are somehow fleecing Cali=
fornia.

In this atmosphere, an interesting, albeit fringe, idea was recently posed =
in=20
a report by economist Peter Navarro of the University of California-Irvine=
=20
and Michael Shames of the San Diego-based consumer group the Utility=20
Consumers' Action Network (UCAN).

"California should join with Oregon and Washington to create a buyers' cart=
el=20
to offset the market power of the Western generators. This multistate buyer=
s'=20
cartel should offer to pay a reasonable price for power to the sellers'=20
cartel members=01*but not a penny more," said the report.

The report named Mirant, Enron, Dynegy, Reliant and Williams Cos. as member=
s=20
of a "sellers' cartel."

While the idea may be organizationally untenable, it nevertheless places th=
e=20
California situation in an interesting conceptual framework, given the=20
politicization of the crisis. It's certainly an approach many politicians=
=20
would rally around if they could figure out a way to use it to reduce OPEC'=
s=20
market influence.

The buyers' cartel
Shames, a consumer advocate, gained notoriety as the author of a 1999 paper=
=20
(posted on UCAN's Web site) that predicted today's energy crisis. He said t=
he=20
idea has garnered a positive response, in some circles.

"Surprisingly so," Shames said. "Supportive sentiments have been echoed by=
=20
the head of DWR [California Department of Water Resources] and a number of=
=20
economists including Paul Krugman in a New York Times op-ed piece." Accordi=
ng=20
to Shames, the recent Senate Bill SBX-73 introduced in California embodies=
=20
the critical elements of the cartel approach.

UCAN proposes the approach only as a backup plan in the event that the=20
Western situation turns catastrophic this summer. "One could view it as an=
=20
insurance policy; it would not need to be used unless the governor's summer=
=20
strategy begins to falter. It contains two elements: creation of a hard-nos=
ed=20
'buyers' cartel' and, if necessary, the forced sale of in-state generation=
=20
plants to the state," said the report.

Each day, a Western states buyers' cooperative would set a price it conside=
rs=20
fair and reasonable, based on the cost of producing electricity, natural ga=
s=20
prices or other fuels, and a generous double-digit profit margin in order t=
o=20
ensure future investment in the power infrastructure.

A power plant operator that wanted to sell electricity in these three Pacif=
ic=20
Coast states would meet the price set by the cooperative. Those who didn't=
=20
like the price could shut down their plants and sit out the market for the=
=20
day, said Shames and Navarro.

For this plan to be effective, the report's authors concede California's=20
legislature would have to pass emergency legislation to modify current law=
=20
requiring California's independent system operator to purchase power "at an=
y=20
price" to keep the lights on.

"This will empower the buyer's cartel to enforce its fair price offer," sai=
d=20
the report. It would also hold consumers hostage to a battle between cartel=
s.

Blackouts as leverage
"The formation of a buyers' cartel will almost certainly spark retaliatory=
=20
blackouts as the sellers' cartel tests the political will of our legislator=
s=20
and governor. Indeed, the bold measures proposed here will require politica=
l=20
fortitude," the report asserts.

To respond to this eventuality, instead of random rolling blackouts sweepin=
g=20
the state without notice, rotating outages would be planned and telegraphed=
=20
ahead of time. "That would give predictability to business and residents,=
=20
which is what most people want. It also would tip off the crooks, of course=
,=20
who might prey on homes suddenly left without alarms. But the cops,=20
forewarned as well, could mobilize ahead of them with extra patrols,"=20
suggests the report.

The authors believe calling the bluff once or twice would be enough to brin=
g=20
costs down to reasonable levels and break the "seller" cartel's market grip=
.

Merchant power companies would have to answer both to stockholders and the=
=20
outrage of public opinion if plants were intentionally idled during a=20
blackout. Blackouts appear to be inevitable this summer due to genuine powe=
r=20
shortages, but this approach would at least contain the price of available=
=20
power according to the logic of the report. The authors say that it's "a pl=
an=20
that a free-market economist could love. Buyers pooling their clout to win =
a=20
better price. People sacrificing to get what they want. Generators free to=
=20
participate, or not."

If the blackouts grew too disruptive, Shames and Navarro said, Gov. Gray=20
Davis and his counterparts in Oregon and Washington would have to use=20
emergency powers to seize the plants that refuse to play the game. That's=
=20
when things would get ugly.

Bunker mentality
The Shames and Navarro proposal has, at its core, a presumption of unfair=
=20
practices by merchant power, something these companies and other economists=
=20
would certainly refute. Ironically, this cartel approach could work in favo=
r=20
of merchant power as well as buyers, demonstrating that blackouts are not=
=20
linked to market manipulation.

Beyond theory, the idea would be difficult from a practical standpoint yet =
it=20
illustrates the growing frustration at many levels with the extraordinary=
=20
Western power market. As the report's authors conclude, by this summer, wit=
h=20
the air conditioning off and California's budget in tatters, "a buyers'=20
cartel could look downright reasonable."=20
